Duo Thruster Test
- Test Thruster 1 and Thruster 3 together as a front pair
- See whether a symmetric pair would move the vehicle upward more cleanly

result:
- The submarine performed a vertical loop like fucking roller coaster
- The pair was still creating strong pitch torque
- The main reason was likely that the corner thrusters are mounted at angles
- Using local marker axes directly caused mismatched force directions
- The front pair alone was not suitable for a clean heave test, I guess

Four Vertical Thruster Test

- Use all 4 corner thrusters together
- Test whether the submarine can move upward in a stable way

Thrusters used:
- Thruster 1
- Thruster 3
- Thruster 7
- Thruster 8

result:
- Still produced looping with a little twist

Possible problem:
- Each corner thruster is mounted at an angle
- Using each thruster marker's local up vector meant the forces were not all truly vertical
- This added forward/back and side components that created looping torque

=========================================================================
Continue on Four Vertical Thruster Test

- Stopped using the local thruster axis for this test
- Applied the same world-space upward force to all 4 vertical thrusters
- Used a shared world direction instead of each marker's tilted direction

result: 

- The vertical loop stopped
- The submarine mostly stayed in place horizontally
- Y position increased slightly
- After unfreezing X and Z rotation, X and Z positions still stayed stable
- Only Y changed
- Increasing the thrust force to 50 made the submarine rise about 1 unit per second
- The 4 vertical thrusters can now produce stable upward heave
- The earlier instability was mainly a force-direction problem, not a general physics failure

